# QUESTION: When two context bindings could satisfy the same need, is that an
# error (incoherence), or does one win by a defined rule (e.g. last-wins)?
#
# `Lower::extract_ty_lambda` (and its sig/val siblings) collect every matching
# slot and then do `if options.len() == 1 { Some(..) } else { None }` -- so
# *zero* matches and *two-or-more* matches are currently treated identically
# (as "not found"). Meanwhile `examples/rebind.moss` shows that a nearer
# binding is allowed to shadow a farther one, which implies overlap is somehow
# tolerated. This probe puts two bindings for the same need *at the same call
# site* so there is no "nearer/farther" tie-breaker.
#
#   Interpretation A — duplicate/overlapping providers are an error:
#                                                                => COMPILE ERROR
#   Interpretation B — last binding wins:                        => prints "second"
#   Interpretation C — first binding wins:                       => prints "first"
#
# ANSWER (confirmed): Interpretation A (COMPILE ERROR). Context is a *stack* of
# context frames; a lookup walks from the top down, and an ambiguity error is
# raised if a single frame holds two candidates with no upper bound (one at
# least as precise as all others). The two bindings here land in the SAME frame
# (one call site), so they're ambiguous. The fix is to put them in different
# frames, which is what `bind` is for:
#
#   fn main() {
#     bind greeting = "first";
#     { bind greeting = "second"; show(); }   # prints "second" (top of stack)
#     show();                                  # prints "first"  (frame below)
#   }
#
# Note `bind a, b;` adds a SINGLE frame, so `bind greeting="first", greeting="second";`
# is itself ambiguous.

assume Std;

val greeting: String;

fn show[greeting]() {
  println(greeting);
}

fn main() {
  show[greeting = "first", greeting = "second"]();
}
